        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your very kind letter.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am very glad of the nature of the work, on which you are employed.— I see so few people that I had not heard of your presence in London.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> At the end of this week I shall be in London at my daughter’s house, &amp; I will on the following week, propose your coming to luncheon, which is generally my best time, &amp; I trust this may not be inconvenient to you.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I did receive the Pop. Science Monthly &amp; read your attack (&amp; an attack it was with a vengeance, though properly admitting his great services) on Agassiz with great interest.<ref target="#foot.f5"/> I have not seen the N. American, &amp; shall be very glad to see it, but I can order a copy for myself.<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>Until we meet | yours very sincerely | Ch Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.2 admitting] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘allowing’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">3.2 seen] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘of course’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n3">2.4 a copy] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘it’ </note>
